            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Three to five KPIs per team or initiative. Company-wide, 5-7 is standard. Tracking more than 10 KPIs at any level is a sign that priorities haven't been set — not a sign of thorough measurement.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What is the difference between a KPI and an OKR?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>OKRs (Objectives and Key Results) are a goal-setting framework. KPIs are the specific metrics you track within that framework. An OKR might be to become the top-ranked site for SEO glossary terms; supporting KPIs would include keyword rankings, organic traffic, and page-one positions.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How often should you review KPIs?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Campaign-level KPIs: weekly. Department-level KPIs: monthly. Company-level KPIs: quarterly. Consistent review cadences enable trend detection and proactive course correction before problems compound.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
